External features: Specimens examined alive ranged in length from 5–8 cm , in width from 0.6 –1.0 mm in normal creeping state before anaesthetization. Body slender, rather voluminous, gradually narrowing near posterior tip of body, ending in bluntly pointed tail (
Fig. 1 A
). Head rounded, wider than succeeding body, possessing four eyes arranged in corners of trapezium (
Fig. 1 B
). No evidence of cephalic furrows on dorsal surface. Body colour milky white, dorsally marked by two dark brown stripes not meeting anteriorly (
Fig. 1 A, B
).
